{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01R4hnhRKvRt8BEBJJH4PmiH","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# CLAUDE.md\n     2→\n     3→This file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.\n     4→\n     5→## Repository Overview\n     6→\n     7→Office-Bohemia is the primary repository for Microsoft Loop, built on the Fluid Framework for real-time collaboration. It's a Yarn-based monorepo (~200 packages) using Lage for task orchestration.\n     8→\n     9→## Documentation\n    10→\n    11→Detailed documentation lives in `./docs/`. Key sections:\n    12→\n    13→- `docs/developer-guide/` - Internal development docs\n    14→- `docs/partner-guide/` - For teams integrating with Loop\n    15→\n    16→## Documentation Ownership\n    17→\n    18→- This file defines **repo-wide** coding agent defaults.\n    19→- App/package-specific behavior should be documented in local docs in that scope.\n    20→- For Bebop work, see `apps/bebop/CLAUDE.md` (automatically includes agent workflow and architecture standards).\n    21→\n    22→## Common Commands\n    23→\n    24→All commands run from repo root. Use `yarn`, not `npm run`. Lage automatically handles prerequisites (build, bundle).\n    25→\n    26→```bash\n    27→# Development\n    28→yarn                              # Install dependencies (run after git pull or branch switch)\n    29→yarn start --to loop-app          # Start Loop app dev server\n    30→yarn build --to <package-name>    # Build up to a specific package\n    31→yarn test --to <package-name>     # Run unit tests\n    32→yarn test:e2e --to <package-name> # Run Playwright e2e tests\n    33→yarn prettier --to <package-name> # Format code\n    34→yarn lint --to <package-name>     # Lint package\n    35→yarn lint --fix --to <package-name> # Lint and auto-fix\n    36→\n    37→# Single test (from package directory)\n    38→yarn test TestFileName.test.ts\n    39→yarn test --testNamePattern \"pattern\"\n    40→yarn test:e2e --file TestFileName.playwright-test.ts\n    41→\n    42→# Faster builds for targeted work\n    43→yarn build --since master         # Only packages changed since master\n    44→yarn test --since master          # Test only changed packages\n    45→yarn build --scope <package-name> # Build package AND all its consumers\n    46→\n    47→# Validation\n    48→yarn validate                     # Full validation (build, lint, test, e2e)\n    49→yarn validate:lint                # Lint-only (faster)\n    50→\n    51→# Maintenance\n    52→yarn clean                        # Clean build artifacts\n    53→yarn scrub                        # Full clean including node_modules\n    54→yarn change                       # Generate change files for PRs\n    55→```\n    56→\n    57→Full script list in `package.json`. See `docs/developer-guide/tooling/yarn-script-reference.md` for details.\n    58→\n    59→### Claude Code Commands\n    60→\n    61→```bash\n    62→/review-branch                    # Review changes on current branch\n    63→/create-pr                        # Create PR for office-bohemia\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→## Code Architecture\n    67→\n    68→### Directory Structure\n    69→\n    70→- `apps/` - Applications (loop-app, bebop, scriptor-pad, test-app)\n    71→- `packages/` - ~200 shared packages\n    72→- `tools/` - Build tooling\n    73→- `azure/` - Deployment configurations\n    74→- `docs/` - Engineering documentation\n    75→\n    76→### Core Architectural Concepts\n    77→\n    78→**Loop Components** are portable, collaborative experiences (LEAP: Live, Embeddable, Actionable, Portable). They render in any M365 host.\n    79→\n    80→**Loop Hosts** are applications that embed Loop Components (Teams, Outlook, Word, Loop App).\n    81→\n    82→**Containers** are Fluid Framework containers - the collaborative data layer. Key containers:\n    83→\n    84→- `loop-page-container` - Powers Loop pages (canvas with Scriptor, Tablero, etc.)\n    85→- `office-fluid-container` - Powers inline Loop components in Teams/Outlook chat\n    86→\n    87→**WorkspaceComponent** (`apps/loop-app/src/WorkspaceComponent/`) is the embedding surface for hosts to render full Loop workspace/page experiences. Hosts like the M365 Copilot App use this to embed Loop experiences without running the full Loop App. Served at `/workspaceComponentManifest.json`.\n    88→\n    89→### Key Packages\n    90→\n    91→| Package | Purpose |\n    92→|---------|---------|\n    93→| `loop-app` | Loop web application (apps/) |\n    94→| `loop-page-container` | Fluid container for Loop pages |\n    95→| `office-fluid-container` | Fluid container for inline components |\n    96→| `scriptor` | Rich text editing engine |\n    97→| `tablero` / `tablero-views` | Table component |\n    98→| `component-ux` | Shared UI components |\n    99→| `loop-app-ux` | Loop app specific UX |\n   100→| `base-container` | Container utilities |\n   101→\n   102→### Testing Container Changes\n   103→\n   104→- **For loop-page-container**: Use `yarn start --to loop-page-container` (demo app at localhost:3000)\n   105→- **For Loop App**: Use `yarn start --to loop-app`\n   106→- **For Teams/Outlook integration**: Use `yarn localDeploy --to loop-page-container` with Fiddler rules (see package README)\n   107→\n   108→**Important**: Loop App bundles loop-page-container. Avoid PRs that span both - this can cause compatibility issues with hosts loading containers from CDN.\n   109→\n   110→## Code Style Guidelines\n   111→\n   112→### TypeScript\n   113→\n   114→- No `as` type assertions, `any` types, or `!` non-null assertions\n   115→- Use `?.` and `??` over traditional null checks\n   116→- Prefer immutable data (`const`, `readonly`)\n   117→\n   118→### React\n   119→\n   120→- Components must be pure (same inputs = same output)\n   121→- `useEffect` only for external systems (APIs, subscriptions, timers) - always include cleanup\n   122→- Never use `useEffect` for derived state\n   123→- Group related state: `useState({ x: 0, y: 0 })`\n   124→- Use status enums over multiple booleans: `'loading' | 'error' | 'success'`\n   125→- Use `useId()` for accessible IDs for components\n   126→\n   127→### Async Code\n   128→\n   129→- Prefer `async/await` over callbacks/promises\n   130→- Use `Promise.all` for parallel execution\n   131→- Avoid `setTimeout` as workaround for race conditions\n   132→\n   133→### Logging\n   134→\n   135→- Use provided logger instance, not `console.log`\n   136→- Log specific fields, not entire objects\n   137→\n   138→### API Design\n   139→\n   140→- Don't break public package APIs\n   141→- Prefer private over public methods/properties\n   142→- Pass optional params as objects, not multiple optional parameters\n   143→\n   144→## Azure DevOps CLI Setup\n   145→\n   146→Many skills/commands use Azure CLI to interact with Azure DevOps. One-time setup:\n   147→\n   148→1. Install Azure CLI: <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/install-azure-cli>\n   149→2. Log in: `az login` (do NOT use `--use-device-code` — not supported by this org)\n   150→3. The shared prereq script (`.claude/scripts/az-prereqs.sh`) handles extension installation and default configuration automatically.\n   151→\n   152→If commands fail with auth errors, run `az login` again (tokens expire after ~60 minutes).\n   153→\n   154→## Testing\n   155→\n   156→- Unit tests: `*.test.ts`\n   157→- Mock all external dependencies\n   158→- Use `jest.useFakeTimers()` instead of real timers\n   159→- E2E tests: `*.playwright-test.ts` - Playwright-based\n   160→- Live tests: `yarn test:e2e:live` - Tests against real endpoints (staging/dogfood/prod)\n   161→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01DLPgnTkmGzXzsDrb5HSUSt","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"951fb598-0462-485e-a920-a2ce9d3d4c61"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NnZ1E4MQK6Vu8RD3UhaEk5","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# OfficeAgent Monorepo\n     2→\n     3→AI agent platform for Office document creation (DOCX, PPTX, XLSX, PDF), running in Docker containers with Claude SDK and Azure OpenAI harnesses.\n     4→\n     5→## Shell Requirements\n     6→\n     7→**CRITICAL: Use PowerShell for all yarn, oagent, and gulp commands.** Bash/sh will fail for build/run operations. File searching (grep, find, glob) works in any shell.\n     8→\n     9→## Repository Structure\n    10→\n    11→- `agents/` - Agent implementations (create-agent, gpt-create-agent, ppt-creation-agent, ppt-edit-agent, dw-accountant-agent, dw-paralegal-agent, odsp-agent)\n    12→- `modules/` - Shared libraries (`@officeagent/*`): core, api, message-protocol, grounding, rai, excel-headless, chain-of-thought, html2pptx, json-to-docx-ooxml, mcp-proxy, gpt-agent, git-remote-spo\n    13→- `.devtools/` - CLI (`oagent`), test-client, e2e-tests, eval-browser, launcher, OCV tools\n    14→- `eval/` - Python evaluation framework (pytest-based)\n    15→- `docs/` - Architecture documentation\n    16→- `docker/` - Dockerfile, runtime package.json, docker-compose\n    17→\n    18→## Build & Run Commands\n    19→\n    20→| Command | Description |\n    21→|---------|-------------|\n    22→| `npm run setup` | First-time dev environment setup |\n    23→| `yarn build` | Build packages + Docker image (Docker Desktop must be running) |\n    24→| `yarn start` | Start Docker container + test client |\n    25→| `yarn start:compose` | Start via docker-compose (supports scaling) |\n    26→| `yarn stop` | Stop Docker container |\n    27→| `yarn reload` | Hot-reload code into running container |\n    28→| `yarn test` | Run all tests (Jest + pytest) |\n    29→| `yarn lint` | ESLint across all workspaces |\n    30→\n    31→## Package Management\n    32→\n    33→- **Buildtime**: Yarn 4.10.3 workspaces with `lage` task runner\n    34→- **Runtime (in container)**: npm for Node packages (`docker/package.json`), pip/tdnf for Python (`docker/Dockerfile`)\n    35→- Packages use `@officeagent/` scope with `workspace:^` linking\n    36→\n    37→## Testing\n    38→\n    39→- **TypeScript/JS**: Jest with ts-jest preset. Tests in `**/tests/**/*.test.ts`\n    40→- **Python**: pytest with coverage. Tests in `tests/test_*.py`. See `docs/PYTHON_TESTING.md`\n    41→- Coverage collected only in CI (`TF_BUILD=true`)\n    42→\n    43→## Agent Architecture (Common Pattern)\n    44→\n    45→Each agent follows this pattern:\n    46→- `src/registry.ts` - Agent config: ID, model, versions, skills, flights, filters\n    47→- `src/<agent-name>.ts` - Main agent implementation\n    48→- `src/prompts/<version>/` - Prompt files, skills (`skills/<name>/SKILL.md`), sub-agents (`subagents/<name>.md`)\n    49→\n    50→Agents register skills, flight-based overrides, and filter rules in `registry.ts`. The `modules/api` module provides the internal handler registry for message routing.\n    51→\n    52→## Environment Configuration\n    53→\n    54→- Copy `.env.example` to `.env` at repo root\n    55→- All config vars use `OAGENT_` prefix (e.g., `OAGENT_AGENTID`, `OAGENT_FLIGHTS`)\n    56→- Default API URL: `http://localhost:6010`\n    57→- Agent selection: `OAGENT_AGENTID=create-agent` (default)\n    58→\n    59→## Logging Rules\n    60→\n    61→- **NEVER** include user data (filenames, content, queries) in `logInfo`, `logWarn`, `logError` -- these go to telemetry\n    62→- `logDebug` is local-only, OK for user data\n    63→- Do not use `console.*` in production code -- ESLint enforces `@officeagent/core` logging\n    64→\n    65→## CLI Tool (`oagent`)\n    66→\n    67→```powershell\n    68→oagent ping                          # Health check\n    69→oagent gen \"<prompt>\" --open         # Generate and open document\n    70→oagent gen \"<prompt>\" -f flag1 flag2 # Generate with flight flags\n    71→oagent config get                    # View configuration\n    72→oagent eval alias                    # List eval aliases\n    73→```\n    74→\n    75→## Workstream-Specific Guidance\n    76→\n    77→See agents/area-specific CLAUDE.md files:\n    78→- `agents/create-agent/CLAUDE.md` - Create Agent (DOCX/PPTX/XLSX, Claude SDK)\n    79→- `agents/gpt-create-agent/CLAUDE.md` - GPT Create Agent (Azure OpenAI variant)\n    80→- `agents/ppt-creation-agent/CLAUDE.md` - PPT Creation Agent\n    81→- `agents/ppt-edit-agent/CLAUDE.md` - PPT Edit Agent\n    82→- `agents/dw-accountant-agent/CLAUDE.md` - DataWorks Accountant Agent\n    83→- `agents/dw-paralegal-agent/CLAUDE.md` - DataWorks Paralegal Agent\n    84→- `agents/odsp-agent/CLAUDE.md` - ODSP Agent\n    85→- `eval/CLAUDE.md` - Evaluation Framework\n    86→\n    87→## Best Practices\n    88→\n    89→See `docs/BEST_PRACTICES.md` for code organization, agent development patterns, testing, build/deploy, and common pitfalls.\n    90→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01TKCt5XCBDve7zLFaUYAVs5","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"73344409-27cc-4e13-996c-cef42ab8d0bc"}
