{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SPZYpN2WpqPCog7aNswPEQ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * @officeagent/orchestrator\n     3→ *\n     4→ * Abstraction layer for multi-provider agent orchestration.\n     5→ * Agents program against IOrchestrator — the factory handles provider selection.\n     6→ */\n     7→\n     8→// Core types\n     9→export {\n    10→    IOrchestrator,\n    11→    OrchestratorRequest,\n    12→    OrchestratorResult,\n    13→    OrchestratorHooks,\n    14→    OrchestratorMessage,\n    15→    OrchestratorUsage,\n    16→    OrchestratorToolInput,\n    17→    OrchestratorToolDecision,\n    18→    OrchestratorToolOutput,\n    19→} from './types';\n    20→\n    21→// Generic tool hooks (provider-agnostic)\n    22→export type {\n    23→    GenericToolHooks,\n    24→    PreToolUseHook,\n    25→    PreToolUseResult,\n    26→    PostToolUseHook,\n    27→    PostToolUseResult,\n    28→    SessionHook,\n    29→    SessionContext,\n    30→} from './types';\n    31→\n    32→// Hook adapters\n    33→export { toClaudeHooks, mergeWithClaudeHooks } from './hooks/claude-hook-adapter';\n    34→\n    35→// Factory\n    36→export {\n    37→    createOrchestrator,\n    38→    registerProvider,\n    39→    unregisterProvider,\n    40→    listProviders,\n    41→} from './factory';\n    42→export type { HarnessType, OrchestratorFactory } from './factory';\n    43→\n    44→// Providers (for direct instantiation when needed)\n    45→export { BaseOrchestrator } from './providers';\n    46→export type { ToolPermissionResult } from './providers';\n    47→export { ClaudeOrchestrator, GhcpOrchestrator } from './providers';\n    48→\n    49→// Adapters\n    50→export { toChainOfThoughtMessage, ChainOfThoughtAdapter } from './cot-adapter';\n    51→\n    52→// Constants\n    53→export { GPT5_MODEL_PREFIX } from './constants';\n    54→\n    55→// Utilities\n    56→export { dynamicImport, getProviderConfig, isOpenAiProvider, isAnthropicProvider } from './utils';\n    57→export type { ProviderConfig } from './utils';\n    58→\n    59→// HarnessBuilder\n    60→export { HarnessBuilder } from './harness-builder';\n    61→\n    62→\n    63→// Env resolvers\n    64→export { buildEnv, ENV_FEATURE_GATES, ENV_SETTING_KEYS } from './env-builder';\n    65→export type { FeatureGateSetting, AgentEnvContext } from './env-builder';\n    66→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01TKCt5XCBDve7zLFaUYAVs5","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"26e51705-ca9c-4de8-8ca1-b56e6df87727"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AbEdxHyVTmcq5hC31T4ifF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Orchestrator abstraction layer types.\n     3→ *\n     4→ * Defines the contract that all orchestrator providers must implement,\n     5→ * enabling agents to be decoupled from any specific AI SDK.\n     6→ */\n     7→\n     8→// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n     9→// Core Orchestrator Interface\n    10→// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n    11→\n    12→/**\n    13→ * Core orchestrator interface.\n    14→ *\n    15→ * Each provider (Claude, GitHub Copilot, etc.) implements this to wrap its SDK\n    16→ * behind a unified API. Agents program against this interface — the factory\n    17→ * handles provider selection at runtime.\n    18→ *\n    19→ * Two execution modes:\n    20→ * - `run()` — batch: returns the final result (simple callers like grounding-agent)\n    21→ * - `runStream()` — streaming: yields each message as it arrives (create-agent, ppt-agent, etc.)\n    22→ */\n    23→export interface IOrchestrator {\n    24→    /**\n    25→     * Execute a prompt and return the final result (batch mode).\n    26→     *\n    27→     * Default implementation delegates to `runStream()` and collects the terminal result.\n    28→     * Providers may override for optimization.\n    29→     *\n    30→     * @param request - The orchestration request containing prompt, config, and hooks\n    31→     * @returns The final result after the orchestrator completes (or fails)\n    32→     */\n    33→    run(request: OrchestratorRequest): Promise<OrchestratorResult>;\n    34→\n    35→    /**\n    36→     * Execute a prompt and stream normalized messages as they arrive.\n    37→     *\n    38→     * The iterable yields `OrchestratorMessage` objects in real-time:\n    39→     * - `system` — session init, metadata\n    40→     * - `assistant` — reasoning / text output\n    41→     * - `tool_use` — tool invocation (name + input)\n    42→     * - `tool_result` — tool output\n    43→     * - `result` — terminal message with embedded `OrchestratorResult`\n    44→     *\n    45→     * The stream ends after yielding a `result`-type message.\n    46→     *\n    47→     * @param request - The orchestration request\n    48→     * @returns An async iterable of normalized messages\n    49→     */\n    50→    runStream(request: OrchestratorRequest): AsyncIterable<OrchestratorMessage>;\n    51→\n    52→    /**\n    53→     * Interrupt a running orchestrator execution.\n    54→     *\n    55→     * Maps to provider-specific abort mechanisms:\n    56→     * - Claude: `queryIterator.interrupt()`\n    57→     * - GHCP: `abortController.abort()`\n    58→     *\n    59→     * Safe to call when not running (no-op).\n    60→     */\n    61→    interrupt(): Promise<void>;\n    62→}\n    63→\n    64→// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n    65→// Request / Result / Message\n    66→// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n    67→\n    68→/**\n    69→ * Input to an orchestrator run.\n    70→ */\n    71→export interface OrchestratorRequest {\n    72→    /** The user prompt to send to the orchestrator */\n    73→    prompt: string;\n    74→    /** User context content to inject as a user message before the prompt */\n    75→    userContext?: string;\n    76→    /** System prompt defining agent behavior */\n    77→    systemPrompt?: string;\n    78→    /** Model identifier (provider-specific, e.g. 'claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929') */\n    79→    model?: string;\n    80→    /** Maximum number of agentic turns before stopping */\n    81→    maxTurns?: number;\n    82→    /**\n    83→     * Reasoning effort level hint.\n    84→     *\n    85→     * Accepts both GHCP ('xhigh') and Claude ('max') top-tier values.\n    86→     * Providers normalize as appropriate:\n    87→     * - GHCP: 'max' → 'xhigh', rest passed directly as `reasoningEffort`\n    88→     * - Claude: 'xhigh' → 'max', rest passed directly as SDK `effort`\n    89→     */\n    90→    reasoningEffort?: 'low' | 'medium' | 'high' | 'max' | 'xhigh';\n    91→    /** List of tools the orchestrator is allowed to use (by name) */\n    92→    allowedTools?: string[];\n    93→    /** List of tools the orchestrator must not use */\n    94→    disallowedTools?: string[];\n    95→    /**\n    96→     * Full tool definitions for providers that require schemas (e.g. GitHub Copilot\n    97→     * function calling). Claude SDK manages its own tool definitions so this is ignored.\n    98→     * Shape is provider-dependent — use `unknown[]` and cast in the provider.\n    99→     */\n   100→    toolDefinitions?: unknown[];\n   101→    /** Working directory for tool execution */\n   102→    cwd?: string;\n   103→    /** Environment variables passed to the orchestrator process */\n   104→    env?: Record<string, string>;\n   105→    /** Abort controller for cancellation */\n   106→    abortController?: AbortController;\n   107→    /** Hooks for observing orchestrator activity (batch mode — used by run()) */\n   108→    hooks?: OrchestratorHooks;\n   109→    /** Provider-agnostic tool hooks for interception (pre/post tool calls) */\n   110→    toolHooks?: GenericToolHooks;\n   111→    /** Session ID for resuming a previous conversation (maps to Claude `resume`) */\n   112→    sessionId?: string;\n   113→    /**\n   114→     * Opaque provider-specific options.\n   115→     *\n   116→     * Examples:\n   117→     * - Claude: `{ continue: true, stderr: Writable, permissionMode: '...' }`\n   118→     * - GHCP: `{ token: '...', confirmationRequired: true }`\n   119→     */\n   120→    providerOptions?: Record<string, unknown>;\n   121→}\n   122→\n   123→/**\n   124→ * Result from an orchestrator run.\n   125→ */\n   126→/**\n   127→ * Standardized usage metrics.\n   128→ *\n   129→ * Providers populate whichever fields they can. The fields are intentionally\n   130→ * all optional — not every SDK exposes every metric.\n   131→ */\n   132→export interface OrchestratorUsage {\n   133→    /** Number of input / prompt tokens consumed */\n   134→    inputTokens?: number;\n   135→    /** Number of output / completion tokens generated */\n   136→    outputTokens?: number;\n   137→    /** Total tokens (input + output) — some providers report this directly */\n   138→    totalTokens?: number;\n   139→    /** Estimated cost in USD for this run */\n   140→    costUsd?: number;\n   141→    /** Wall-clock duration of the run in milliseconds */\n   142→    durationMs?: number;\n   143→    /** Number of agentic turns executed */\n   144→    turnCount?: number;\n   145→}\n   146→\n   147→export interface OrchestratorResult {\n   148→    /** The final text content produced by the orchestrator */\n   149→    content: string;\n   150→    /** Execution status */\n   151→    status: 'completed' | 'exhausted' | 'failed' | 'aborted';\n   152→    /** Provider session ID (for resuming conversations) */\n   153→    sessionId?: string;\n   154→    /** Error message if status is 'failed' */\n   155→    error?: string;\n   156→    /**\n   157→     * Standardized usage metrics.\n   158→     *\n   159→     * Providers populate whichever fields they can from the SDK response.\n   160→     * Use this for dashboards, cost tracking, and performance analysis.\n   161→     */\n   162→    usage?: OrchestratorUsage;\n   163→    /** Provider-specific metadata (e.g. non-standard SDK data) */\n   164→    metadata?: Record<string, unknown>;\n   165→}\n   166→\n   167→/** Input describing a tool about to be (or just) executed. */\n   168→export interface OrchestratorToolInput {\n   169→    toolName: string;\n   170→    toolArgs: Record<string, unknown>;\n   171→    toolUseId?: string;\n   172→}\n   173→\n   174→/** Decision returned by onPreToolUse — allow or block tool execution. */\n   175→export interface OrchestratorToolDecision {\n   176→    allow: boolean;\n   177→    reason?: string;\n   178→    /** Message injected into agent conversation when blocking */\n   179→    injectMessage?: string;\n   180→}\n   181→\n   182→/** Output from a completed tool execution. */\n   183→export interface OrchestratorToolOutput {\n   184→    toolName: string;\n   185→    success: boolean;\n   186→    /** Token usage for this tool turn (if provider supplies it) */\n   187→    usage?: {\n   188→        inputTokens?: number;\n   189→        outputTokens?: number;\n   190→        cacheReadTokens?: number;\n   191→        cacheWriteTokens?: number;\n   192→    };\n   193→}\n   194→\n   195→/**\n   196→ * Hooks for observing orchestrator messages in real-time (batch mode).\n   197→ *\n   198→ * Used by `run()` to forward messages to consumers without requiring\n   199→ * them to consume the streaming iterable. For streaming mode, consumers\n   200→ * iterate the `AsyncIterable<OrchestratorMessage>` directly.\n   201→ */\n   202→export interface OrchestratorHooks {\n   203→    /** Called for each message the orchestrator produces */\n   204→    onMessage?: (message: OrchestratorMessage) => void | Promise<void>;\n   205→    /** Called when the orchestrator encounters an error */\n   206→    onError?: (error: Error) => void;\n   207→    /** Called before a tool executes — return allow/deny decision */\n   208→    onPreToolUse?: (input: OrchestratorToolInput) => Promise<OrchestratorToolDecision>;\n   209→    /** Called after a tool completes — for tracking/telemetry */\n   210→    onPostToolUse?: (input: OrchestratorToolInput, output: OrchestratorToolOutput) => void | Promise<void>;\n   211→}\n   212→\n   213→/**\n   214→ * A normalized message emitted by the orchestrator during execution.\n   215→ *\n   216→ * All provider-specific message shapes are normalized into this format.\n   217→ * The `raw` field preserves the original provider message for advanced\n   218→ * consumers that need provider-specific details (e.g. thinking tokens, cost).\n   219→ */\n   220→export interface OrchestratorMessage {\n   221→    /** Message type */\n   222→    type: 'assistant' | 'tool_use' | 'tool_result' | 'thinking' | 'system' | 'result' | 'progress';\n   223→    /** Text content of the message */\n   224→    content?: string;\n   225→    /** Tool name (for tool_use / tool_result types) */\n   226→    toolName?: string;\n   227→    /** Tool input arguments (for tool_use type) */\n   228→    toolInput?: unknown;\n   229→    /** Subtype for finer discrimination (e.g. 'init', 'success', 'error_max_turns') */\n   230→    subtype?: string;\n   231→    /** Embedded result (populated when type === 'result') */\n   232→    result?: OrchestratorResult;\n   233→    /** Duration in milliseconds (populated on result messages) */\n   234→    durationMs?: number;\n   235→    /** Session ID (populated on system init messages) */\n   236→    sessionId?: string;\n   237→    /** Raw provider-specific message for advanced consumers */\n   238→    raw?: unknown;\n   239→}\n   240→\n   241→// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   242→// Generic Tool Hooks (provider-agnostic hook interception)\n   243→// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   244→\n   245→/**\n   246→ * Provider-agnostic tool hook interface.\n   247→ *\n   248→ * Adapters translate these generic hooks into provider-specific formats:\n   249→ * - Claude: `Options['hooks']` with `PreToolUse`/`PostToolUse` arrays\n   250→ *\n   251→ * This allows hook providers (ppt-hooks, word-hooks, excel-hooks, etc.)\n   252→ * to be written once and work across all orchestrator providers.\n   253→ */\n   254→export interface GenericToolHooks {\n   255→    /**\n   256→     * Called before a tool is executed.\n   257→     *\n   258→     * @param toolName - Name of the tool about to be invoked\n   259→     * @param input - Tool input arguments\n   260→     * @returns Decision: continue execution (optionally with modified input), or block\n   261→     */\n   262→    preToolUse?: PreToolUseHook[];\n   263→\n   264→    /**\n   265→     * Called after a tool completes execution.\n   266→     *\n   267→     * @param toolName - Name of the tool that was invoked\n   268→     * @param output - Tool execution result\n   269→     * @returns Decision: continue or block further processing\n   270→     */\n   271→    postToolUse?: PostToolUseHook[];\n   272→\n   273→    /** Called when the orchestrator session starts */\n   274→    onSessionStart?: SessionHook[];\n   275→\n   276→    /** Called when the orchestrator session ends */\n   277→    onSessionEnd?: SessionHook[];\n   278→}\n   279→\n   280→/**\n   281→ * A single pre-tool-use hook function.\n   282→ */\n   283→export type PreToolUseHook = (\n   284→    toolName: string,\n   285→    input: unknown\n   286→) => Promise<PreToolUseResult> | PreToolUseResult;\n   287→\n   288→/**\n   289→ * Result from a pre-tool-use hook.\n   290→ */\n   291→export interface PreToolUseResult {\n   292→    /** Whether to continue with tool execution */\n   293→    continue: boolean;\n   294→    /** Optionally modified input to pass to the tool (if continue is true) */\n   295→    modifiedInput?: unknown;\n   296→    /** Optional replacement output to use instead of executing the tool (if continue is false) */\n   297→    replacementOutput?: string;\n   298→    /** Optional reason for blocking (logged for diagnostics) */\n   299→    reason?: string;\n   300→}\n   301→\n   302→/**\n   303→ * A single post-tool-use hook function.\n   304→ */\n   305→export type PostToolUseHook = (\n   306→    toolName: string,\n   307→    output: unknown\n   308→) => Promise<PostToolUseResult> | PostToolUseResult;\n   309→\n   310→/**\n   311→ * Result from a post-tool-use hook.\n   312→ */\n   313→export interface PostToolUseResult {\n   314→    /** Whether to continue normal processing */\n   315→    continue: boolean;\n   316→    /** Optionally modified output to feed back to the LLM */\n   317→    modifiedOutput?: unknown;\n   318→}\n   319→\n   320→/**\n   321→ * Context passed to session lifecycle hooks.\n   322→ */\n   323→export interface SessionContext {\n   324→    /** Session ID if available */\n   325→    sessionId?: string;\n   326→    /** Arbitrary metadata for the session */\n   327→    metadata?: Record<string, unknown>;\n   328→}\n   329→\n   330→/**\n   331→ * A session lifecycle hook function.\n   332→ *\n   333→ * Receives optional session context so providers can pass session-specific\n   334→ * information (auth tokens, metadata, etc.) to hook consumers.\n   335→ */\n   336→export type SessionHook = (context?: SessionContext) => Promise<void> | void;\n   337→\n   338→\n   339→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01TKCt5XCBDve7zLFaUYAVs5","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"ee38743b-eb56-4d03-87c0-9d343c4d7475"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B94XydpPjQASq7b57szFGX","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Base abstract class for orchestrator providers.\n     3→ *\n     4→ * Provides default `run()` delegation to `runStream()` and a hook adaptation\n     5→ * extension point. Partner teams extend this when building their own providers —\n     6→ * they only need to implement `runStream()` and `interrupt()`.\n     7→ *\n     8→ * @example\n     9→ * ```typescript\n    10→ * class MyOrchestrator extends BaseOrchestrator {\n    11→ *     async *runStream(request: OrchestratorRequest): AsyncIterable<OrchestratorMessage> {\n    12→ *         // provider-specific streaming implementation\n    13→ *     }\n    14→ *     async interrupt(): Promise<void> {\n    15→ *         // provider-specific abort\n    16→ *     }\n    17→ * }\n    18→ * ```\n    19→ */\n    20→\n    21→import {\n    22→    IOrchestrator,\n    23→    OrchestratorRequest,\n    24→    OrchestratorResult,\n    25→    OrchestratorMessage,\n    26→    GenericToolHooks,\n    27→} from '../types';\n    28→\n    29→/**\n    30→ * Result from a tool permission check.\n    31→ */\n    32→export type ToolPermissionResult =\n    33→    | { allowed: true }\n    34→    | { allowed: false; reason: string };\n    35→\n    36→export abstract class BaseOrchestrator implements IOrchestrator {\n    37→    /** Provider configuration passed at construction. */\n    38→    protected config?: Record<string, unknown>;\n    39→\n    40→    constructor(config?: Record<string, unknown>) {\n    41→        this.config = config;\n    42→    }\n    43→\n    44→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n    45→    // Abstract methods — providers MUST implement\n    46→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n    47→\n    48→    /**\n    49→     * Execute a prompt and stream normalized messages as they arrive.\n    50→     * This is the primary execution method that all providers must implement.\n    51→     */\n    52→    abstract runStream(request: OrchestratorRequest): AsyncIterable<OrchestratorMessage>;\n    53→\n    54→    /**\n    55→     * Interrupt a running orchestrator execution.\n    56→     * Safe to call when not running (should no-op).\n    57→     */\n    58→    abstract interrupt(): Promise<void>;\n    59→\n    60→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n    61→    // Default run() — delegates to runStream()\n    62→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n    63→\n    64→    /**\n    65→     * Execute a prompt and return the final result (batch mode).\n    66→     *\n    67→     * Default implementation iterates `runStream()`, forwards messages to\n    68→     * `hooks.onMessage`, and captures the terminal `result` message.\n    69→     * Providers may override for optimization.\n    70→     */\n    71→    async run(request: OrchestratorRequest): Promise<OrchestratorResult> {\n    72→        let finalResult: OrchestratorResult = {\n    73→            content: '',\n    74→            status: 'completed',\n    75→        };\n    76→\n    77→        try {\n    78→            for await (const message of this.runStream(request)) {\n    79→                // Forward to batch-mode hooks\n    80→                if (request.hooks?.onMessage) {\n    81→                    await request.hooks.onMessage(message);\n    82→                }\n    83→\n    84→                // Capture the terminal result\n    85→                if (message.type === 'result' && message.result) {\n    86→                    finalResult = message.result;\n    87→                }\n    88→            }\n    89→        } catch (err: unknown) {\n    90→            finalResult.status = 'failed';\n    91→            finalResult.error = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);\n    92→            request.hooks?.onError?.(err instanceof Error ? err : new Error(String(err)));\n    93→        }\n    94→\n    95→        return finalResult;\n    96→    }\n    97→\n    98→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n    99→    // Hook adaptation extension point\n   100→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n   101→\n   102→    /**\n   103→     * Translate generic tool hooks to the provider's SDK-specific format.\n   104→     *\n   105→     * Override in providers that support tool hooks. The return type is\n   106→     * `unknown` because each SDK has a different hooks shape.\n   107→     *\n   108→     * @param _genericHooks - Provider-agnostic tool hooks to adapt\n   109→     * @returns Provider-specific hooks object (e.g. Claude Options['hooks'])\n   110→     */\n   111→    protected adaptToolHooks(_genericHooks: GenericToolHooks): unknown {\n   112→        return {};\n   113→    }\n   114→\n   115→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n   116→    // Tool permission enforcement utility\n   117→    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------\n   118→\n   119→    /**\n   120→     * Check whether a tool is allowed by the request's `allowedTools` and\n   121→     * `disallowedTools` lists.\n   122→     *\n   123→     * This is a reusable utility for providers whose SDK does **not** natively\n   124→     * enforce tool permissions (e.g. GitHub Copilot SDK). Providers\n   125→     * whose SDK handles this natively (Claude) can skip calling this.\n   126→     *\n   127→     * Logic:\n   128→     * 1. If `disallowedTools` contains the tool → **blocked**.\n   129→     * 2. If `allowedTools` is defined and does **not** contain the tool → **blocked**.\n   130→     * 3. Otherwise → **allowed**.\n   131→     *\n   132→     * Call this in your `adaptToolHooks()` override or in a pre-tool-use hook.\n   133→     *\n   134→     * @param toolName - The name of the tool being invoked\n   135→     * @param request - The orchestrator request containing allow/disallow lists\n   136→     * @returns `{ allowed: true }` or `{ allowed: false, reason: string }`\n   137→     *\n   138→     * @example\n   139→     * ```typescript\n   140→     * const check = this.checkToolPermission('bash', request);\n   141→     * if (!check.allowed) {\n   142→     *     return { decision: 'block', reason: check.reason };\n   143→     * }\n   144→     * ```\n   145→     */\n   146→    protected checkToolPermission(toolName: string, request: OrchestratorRequest): ToolPermissionResult {\n   147→        // Disallowed list takes priority\n   148→        if (request.disallowedTools && request.disallowedTools.includes(toolName)) {\n   149→            return {\n   150→                allowed: false,\n   151→                reason: `Tool '${toolName}' is in the disallowedTools list`,\n   152→            };\n   153→        }\n   154→\n   155→        // If an allow-list is provided, tool must be on it\n   156→        if (request.allowedTools && !request.allowedTools.includes(toolName)) {\n   157→            return {\n   158→                allowed: false,\n   159→                reason: `Tool '${toolName}' is not in the allowedTools list`,\n   160→            };\n   161→        }\n   162→\n   163→        return { allowed: true };\n   164→    }\n   165→}\n   166→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01TKCt5XCBDve7zLFaUYAVs5","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"81635a92-5dab-403f-9e05-56b8cd66b0aa"}
