{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BJFwzMzjaf4sBSdiudt2Qx","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Copilot Component\n     2→\n     3→* Engineers: Ransom Richardson, Christina Long, Omar Tuffaha, Moiz Ghadiyali, Yang Wang\n     4→* PMs: Ben Wilde, Jenna Hong, Theo Lorrain-Hale\n     5→* Designers: Paul Scudieri, Ryan Lawrence, Susanne Duswald, Paul Baigts\n     6→* AS: Alexey Romanov, Courtney Cochrane\n     7→* UR: Katie Rotella\n     8→* Review: [Design Pull Request](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_git/office-bohemia/pullrequest/1743618)\n     9→* [Backlog](https://dev.azure.com/office/OC/_backlogs/backlog/Copilot/Backlog%20Items)\n    10→\n    11→## Background\n    12→\n    13→We formed this team to deliver a feature for interacting with LLMs in Loop. Our schedule:\n    14→\n    15→* Project Start: Mon, Jan 9\n    16→* Staging: Fri, Feb 3\n    17→* Dogfood: Fri, Feb 17\n    18→* Public Preview Ready: Fri, Mar 3\n    19→* Available: Wed, Mar 15\n    20→\n    21→This design concept exploration video shows some of the long term vision for this project.\n    22→[Copilot Loop-V1](https://microsofteur-my.sharepoint.com/:v:/g/personal/sduswald_microsoft_com/ERBgCTJBo8ZIsJeDfph3pbMB-jNka7xOffEOUzCYtEoCqw?e=evzI9s)\n    23→\n    24→[Figma](https://www.figma.com/file/YlAS6pru4ujzPYU4l3cdY1/Copilot-AI-Spec?node-id=1799%3A1343&t=bA5RlNdvDzGPnV1K-0)\n    25→\n    26→We believe that we can deliver transformative and differentiating value with this solution.\n    27→We are excited about the long-term vision, which is to build a way to interact with LLMs which is:\n    28→\n    29→* Multiplayer/Collaborative\n    30→  * Build on one another’s prompts in real time\n    31→* Steerable\n    32→  * Prompts can be refined, OR the suggested content itself can be modified and fed back into the LLMs\n    33→* Intent-based\n    34→  * We suggest JTBD-related prompt suggestions based on your current context\n    35→* Scalable to more JTBD\n    36→  * We’re starting with some purely generative JTBD, but plan to build this as a framework that can scale\n    37→* Leverages AI attribution\n    38→  * See what content was provided by the AI to help with trust\n    39→* Portable\n    40→  * We’re leveraging Loop Component portability to support similar interactions in hosts across the M365 ecosystem\n    41→\n    42→## Problem Statement\n    43→\n    44→Deliver a way to interact with LLMs in Loop which is:\n    45→\n    46→* **Productive** - LLM capabilities generate content which accelerates customers' ability to accomplish their jobs\n    47→* **Approachable** - We augment the prompt interface with context-relevant suggestions and history to make it easy to use LLMs productively\n    48→* **Transparent** - It is clear what content is generated by the LLM and what the limitations of that could be\n    49→* **Collaborative** - Customers can leverage the collaborative features of Loop to see what the AI generated and how it was created\n    50→\n    51→For public preview, we are focused on user scenarios for content creation.\n    52→The typical flow:\n    53→\n    54→1. User adds the copilot component to a page in the Loop App.\n    55→2. The component will appear in an expanded mode for the creator.\n    56→3. The component will appear in a minimized mode for other endpoints. Minimized mode does not show the *working content*.\n    57→4. The user can see JTBD-focused suggestions of things the LLM can be asked to create.\n    58→5. User makes an *initial ask* of the LLM to generate some content.\n    59→6. The LLM response becomes the *working content*.\n    60→7. The user can directly edit the *working content*.\n    61→8. The user can ask the LLM to refine the *working content* by sending the LLM a *refining ask*.\n    62→9. The user can see suggestions of *refining asks*.\n    63→10. The response to the *refining ask* will become the new *working content*.\n    64→11. There is a history list showing the chronological list of asks which produced the *working content*.\n    65→12. Users can select items in the history list to see view only versions of the history.\n    66→13. Users can delete the most recent item in the history list.\n    67→14. The user may add the component to the canvas. Once added to the canvas the default view is a collapsed mode which shows the most recent *working content*.\n    68→15. *Working content* is editable in collapsed mode.\n    69→16. Users can expand from collapsed mode to expanded mode. In this mode they see all history and can interact with the component as above, including making additional asks, editing, and deleting content.\n    70→17. The component will clearly show that the content was generated in collaboration with the LLM.\n    71→18. Attribution in the content of the component will show which was generated by the LLM and which was authored by a user.\n    72→\n    73→**TODO**: Link to more complete scenarios/user stories\n    74→\n    75→## Design Requirements\n    76→\n    77→This is a large feature, so in this requirements section we focus on those that are of particular technical interest.\n    78→\n    79→1. Copilot component is available in the Loop app\n    80→   1. We expect the full experience to work in other hosts. Fallback experience option for users not opted-in to AI experiences and platforms/apps without full support is to prevent expansion into expanded mode.\n    81→2. Rich editing support for working content\n    82→3. User is able to interact with the LLM\n    83→4. Suggestions are provided for interacting with the LLM\n    84→5. History of asks and working content is stored\n    85→6. Attribution shows which content was content generated by the LLM and which has been edited by humans\n    86→\n    87→## Proposed Solutions (including alternative solutions considered)\n    88→\n    89→### UX Modes and States\n    90→\n    91→[UX Modes and States](../../../packages/copilot/docs/UXStates.md)\n    92→\n    93→### Component Registration\n    94→\n    95→The Copilot component will be added to Loop Page Container.\n    96→\n    97→### Rich Editing Support\n    98→\n    99→We will use an embedded Scriptor component for the working content.\n   100→\n   101→### LLM Interaction\n   102→\n   103→1. All interaction with the LLM will be through AugLoop.\n   104→2. We will build a new AugLoop workflow to support this scenario.\n   105→3. The workflow will perform responsible AI checks on model input and output but otherwise be a passthrough.\n   106→   1. We will use a [SingleItemWorkflow](https://web.augloop-tools.officeppe.com/api/classes/_augloop_api_workflows.SingleItemWorkflow).\n   107→4. Prompt engineering (converting working content, ask, and history into a prompt) will occur in Loop.\n   108→   1. Later this may transition to the server, but we expect to need to iterate and experiment with the prompt engineering and the velocity will be faster when it is performed on the client.\n   109→5. Long-term the workflow will become more sophisticated. For example it will need to support including page content within the prompt. That will require implementing the prompt engineering with the workflow, but that is out of scope for public preview. Alex Polyakov is leading the design to meet these longer term requirements.\n   110→6. Model request are slow (~5s) and there are a number of expected failure conditions. Waits can be canceled and errors retried.\n   111→\n   112→### Ask Suggestions\n   113→\n   114→In the initial implementation, ask suggestions will be from a static list of curated suggestions for initial and refinement ask. There may be some simple heuristics applied.\n   115→\n   116→Over time (after public preview) suggestions may be contextual and personalized.\n   117→\n   118→### History of Asks and Working Content\n   119→\n   120→1. We will use a SharedTree DDS to store the linear history of asks and working content.\n   121→2. Working content will be saved to history after each response from the model.\n   122→3. The following fields will be stored on each tree node:\n   123→   1. **id** - string (GUID) - id of the item\n   124→   2. **parent** - string (GUID) - id of the parent of the item.\n   125→      1. For refining asks, the parent is the working content that was refined.\n   126→      2. It is possible that the working content of the parent was edited after the prompt was created. Thus it is not always possible to reconstruct the prompt from the history information.\n   127→   3. **ask** - string - user ask. This is shown in the history.\n   128→   4. **mlResponse** - string - response from the model.\n   129→   5. **workingContentHandle** - IFluidHandle - handle to the Working Content (Scriptor). The content of this scriptor is set to the mlResponse. It may be subsequently edited by the user. This Scriptor instance is created and the initial content is set before the item is added to the history. An alternative would be to store the handle on first edit, but that would have a race condition if two endpoints made the first edit simultaneously. Creating the handle before storing the item ensures that all endpoints edit in the same Scriptor instance.\n   130→   6. **contentChanged** - boolean - true once the working content is edited. When the content is edited we show two rows in the history view for this one entry in the stored model history.\n   131→4. Simultaneous actions (Conflicts). In the event of conflicts, we ensure that no data which had been persisted is lost, that no data is persisted which is not visible in the UI, and that all endpoints are in a consistent state.\n   132→   1. When making a model request we enter the waiting state. If we receive a new history item from another endpoint, we leave the waiting state. We will then discard the model response when it arrives.\n   133→   2. When in the waiting state, if we receive the first edit to the working content, the history has changed, we leave the waiting state, and will discard the model response.\n   134→   3. When in the waiting state, if the item has already been edited and we receive another edit to the item, it does not change the history, and the model response will not be discarded. This is arguably inconsistent with the previous behavior. I believe it is acceptable for the initial experience. It may be revisited in the future.\n   135→   4. If two model requests occur simultaneously both responses may be added as independent items in the history. We use the default conflict resolution of the Shared Tree (the history will be ordered by the time they arrive at the Fluid relay server).\n   136→\n   137→A previous iteration of the UX design was much more restricted and made conflicts much less likely. In that design we considered an alternative in which we had a single Scriptor instance, stored string contents on the history item, and replaced the contents of the Scriptor with those strings. This may have performed better than creating independent Scriptor instances for each history item, but with the current requirements could result in lost data on conflicts.\n   138→\n   139→### Attribution\n   140→\n   141→When setting content which came from the LLM we will use the postInsertText API and manually set the attribution property to indicate that the text came from the LLM.\n   142→Attribution code already uses this property and will correspondingly attribute the text to Copilot.\n   143→\n   144→We considered an alternative implementation of adding additional information to the existing attribution property. That would have been a more general extension of attribution data and required additional technical design work. We also considered another implementation of adding an additional property that would indicate the text came from the LLM but decided that it wasn't necessary because we already have the attribution property. We decided that using the existing attribution property is the best and simplest solution.\n   145→\n   146→## New Contracts/Public APIs\n   147→\n   148→1. Existing attribution properties will be used to attribute text to Copilot.\n   149→   1. We will use a hard-coded Fluid user which has been added to attribution-provider for this\n   150→   2. To set the property we will call postInsertText on Scriptor. Ideally we could use the setText method, but that currently does not support setting the TextProperties. The potential interface change to setText is tracked by work item 7575648.\n   151→2. New AugLoop workflow to support this scenario.\n   152→\n   153→## Data & Backwards Compatibility\n   154→\n   155→This is a new component which stores data both in the root SharedDirectory and in a SharedTree DDS.\n   156→The handle to the SharedTree is stored in the root SharedDirectory.\n   157→\n   158→In addition, this component uses nested Scriptor components.\n   159→Handles to the Scriptor components are stored in the SharedTree.\n   160→\n   161→It has no other unique backwards compatibility requirements.\n   162→\n   163→## Service / Package Dependencies & Security\n   164→\n   165→Dependency on new AugLoop workflow. This is specific to this feature and will be developed by this feature crew.\n   166→\n   167→No changes to authentication, connection boundaries, or communication endpoints.\n   168→\n   169→## Accessibility\n   170→\n   171→No unique accessibility requirements. Requirements tracked in backlog.\n   172→\n   173→## Mobile Ship Bar\n   174→\n   175→Ideally we will have a fully functional mobile experience. If that is not feasible to accomplish in the public preview timeframe, we will fallback to a mobile experience which allows viewing and editing the latest working content but not interacting with the LLM or history.\n   176→\n   177→## Performance\n   178→\n   179→### Optimized Collapsed Mode\n   180→\n   181→The copilot component code will only be loaded when a page is opened that contains the Copilot component. (Note that even if the component is removed from the page it may still be loaded until summarize and GC are complete). To minimize the load time impact on pages which do contain the copilot component, we will optimize for Collapsed mode.\n   182→\n   183→In most cases the default UX Mode will be Collapsed or Minimized (for simplicity we will refer to that as collapsed for the remainder of this section). We will optimize for the collapsed mode and only load the minimal code and required to display in the collapsed mode. This includes:\n   184→\n   185→1. Not loading history when in the collapsed mode. To enable this we will store the current working content handle in the root of the component shared directory. This avoids loading any SharedTree code or data.\n   186→2. Not initializing our AugLoop session when in collapsed mode. This avoids loading our AugLoop code and types.\n   187→3. Not loading the more complex ViewModel code. The UX State machine and history code in the ViewModel are not needed in the collapsed state.\n   188→4. Not loading the majority of the View code which is only needed for the Expanded state.\n   189→\n   190→#### Questions (Optimized Collapsed Mode)\n   191→\n   192→1. How do we measure the impact of optimizing for collapsed mode?\n   193→2. How do we set up automated checks to ensure that we do not accidentally regress this optimization?\n   194→3. Priority of this work. I currently consider this nice to have but not required for public preview.\n   195→\n   196→### Runtime Performance Impact\n   197→\n   198→Copilot component will have no performance impact on pages which do not use the component.\n   199→\n   200→Copilot component is a typical component, so will be rendered on pages which do have the component. See section above for optimizations to minimize impact in typical usage.\n   201→\n   202→#### Worst Case Performance\n   203→\n   204→1. Pages with many copilot components. We expect the impact of this to be similar to other components. Optimization for collapsed mode should help with this.\n   205→2. Default expanded mode. The component will start in expanded mode only for the creator of the component before it is added to the canvas. In this mode the collapsed optimizations will not help. As it only expects the creator in this mode and only until the component initial usage is finished we expect the impact to be acceptable. This is something we will monitor as part of our feature success telemetry.\n   206→3. Large history. In expanded mode, the component loads all history of interactions with the model. In typical usage we expect this to be limited (<10 items). We will monitor telemetry on history size to verify this as well as measure impact.\n   207→\n   208→#### Notable External Packages\n   209→\n   210→1. fluentui/react\n   211→2. fluid-experimental/tree\n   212→3. augloop-types/copilot\n   213→\n   214→### Bundle size impact\n   215→\n   216→1. fluentui/react - for initial UI implementation it looks like roughly 12k of bundle size increase from UI components. This may increase over time as we implement additional UI. Mitigated by minimized mode optimization.\n   217→2. fluid-experimental/tree - this is already included by Conversa so no increase in the size of the container bundle.\n   218→3. augloop-types/copilot - 9k increase in bundle size. I think this is typical for augloop-type packages, of which we include a number already in the bundle. This seems large for what we get from the package, so at some point in the future may want to follow up with the augloop team on ways to reduce this across features that use AL.\n   219→4. icons - initial icon sets were 5k. These are shared across and loaded by all components, so this increases bundle size across all containers. We are in discussions about how to make these icons specific to our package.\n   220→\n   221→### Telemetry and Goals\n   222→\n   223→Feature success telemetry is covered below. Performance specific telemetry will focus on:\n   224→\n   225→|scenario|goal|notes|\n   226→|----|----|----|\n   227→|component load (collapsed)|<110% Scriptor load time, <100ms (80%)| |\n   228→|component create|<100ms (80%)| |\n   229→|component initial expand|<500ms (80%)|Initial expand only - loads code|\n   230→|all other UI interactions which change mode/state|<100ms (80%)| |\n   231→|history load time|<2ms per item| |\n   232→\n   233→Monitoring of performance metrics will be included in component dashboard. Exact details TODO.\n   234→\n   235→#### Questions (Telemetry and Goals)\n   236→\n   237→1. Are there typical component benchmarks we could base these on?\n   238→2. What are the Scriptor performance benchmarks - will be limited by those for many scenarios.\n   239→3. Are there best practices for measuring these, particularly how to measure when render is complete for a component?\n   240→\n   241→### Additional Performance Considerations\n   242→\n   243→1. LLM interactions are high latency (~5s). This is a limitation of current technology. This is mitigated by waiting UX design which is cancelable.\n   244→2. We expect Scriptor load time to be the limiting factor for most of our performance scenarios.\n   245→\n   246→## Staying Aware and Notifications\n   247→\n   248→1. No notifications are needed\n   249→2. @-mentions may be used in working content to notify other users\n   250→3. If there is a LLM request after the @-mention, the mention will not be in the latest working content. **TODO** Verify that this behaves like other experiences where a @-mention is deleted and that the experience is acceptable. Alternatively, we could disable @-mentions in working content.\n   251→4. Attribution support for LLM made edits described above\n   252→\n   253→## Flighting\n   254→\n   255→'copilot.enabled' - Component feature flag.\n   256→AI Enabled - for public preview there will be an additional setting required to enable AI features.\n   257→\n   258→A user who does not have both the feature flag and the AI enabled setting will:\n   259→\n   260→1. Not be able to create a copilot component\n   261→2. Not be able to expand an existing copilot component. This prevents interaction with the history and the LLM.\n   262→3. Can view and edit the working content for copilot components which are added to the canvas.\n   263→\n   264→## Feature Observability\n   265→\n   266→[Feature Success Telemetry Plan](https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/:fl:/s/a59f31a7-9fc0-45d3-9821-55aaf54ee316/EeqDAt4FDFJEo_VsoSouBNYBdpOJjR1-BZOO3I9hwTv_Ww?e=eUUeme&%3D%3D)\n   267→\n   268→For public preview we will not be collecting customer content signals.\n   269→This data will have very high value for improving the feature, especially the prompt engineering, so adding this will be a high priority improvement.\n   270→It is out of scope of this technical design.\n   271→\n   272→Initial monitoring will use the default component health dashboard: [ComponentHealth.md](../telemetry/ComponentReliability/ComponentHealth.md).\n   273→Additional data and monitoring TBD.\n   274→\n   275→[Test Plan](../../../packages/copilot/docs/TestPlan.md)\n   276→\n   277→## Privacy\n   278→\n   279→Requiring privacy review:\n   280→\n   281→1. Attribution of content to LLM\n   282→\n   283→In addition, Responsible AI review will be required.\n   284→\n   285→## Globalization\n   286→\n   287→LLM will be English only. non-English requests will result in an error.\n   288→\n   289→**TODO** May need to restrict to North America users\n   290→\n   291→No other unique concerns.\n   292→\n   293→## Next Steps\n   294→\n   295→This section should be filled in as the design review progresses. It should include specific next steps, ADO items and timelines for after the design docs has been finalized.\n   296→\n   297→### Performance Review Notes\n   298→\n   299→* To measure render complete:\n   300→  * Wait for notification from scriptor that it has updated\n   301→  * Request animation frame\n   302→  * Make sure that any loading UX is finished\n   303→* To ensure render time rolls up properly make sure to only resolve the render promise once render is complete.\n   304→* Someone (probably Andrew Stegmaier) will be looking at how components hosted in Scriptor report perf telemetry and adding common infrastructure\n   305→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUCvAHSXRtjX93sY9sKE3i","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"052a1618-2b5e-4807-9480-ed8147045257"}
{"type":"system","subtype":"task_progress","task_id":"a089a214341e4c6d6","tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUCvAHSXRtjX93sY9sKE3i","description":"Finding C:/Users/yemishin/office-bohemia/docs/partner-gui…","usage":{"total_tokens":60167,"tool_uses":20,"duration_ms":79201},"last_tool_name":"Glob","uuid":"1682a152-2a9e-46eb-813b-4121b4cdafa4","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01314SxUepDJDYKBWSDKy6DX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AemDoaHDFPvttcsaMwest9","name":"Glob","input":{"pattern":"C:/Users/yemishin/office-bohemia/docs/partner-guide/hosting/*.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2525,"cache_read_input_tokens":57603,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2525,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUCvAHSXRtjX93sY9sKE3i","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"cacc3373-6490-46dc-9ddb-d35661fe810b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01T7v7AJoV7cTZDtzQWuqbFh","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Copilot Page Summary\n     2→\n     3→* Engineers: Eric Frackleton, Sumara Ali, Lyndsy Stopa (EM)\n     4→* PMs: Manish Shukla\n     5→* Designers: Lauren Low\n     6→* AS: Yishuang Chen, Yang He\n     7→* UR: Katie Rotella\n     8→* Review: [Design Pull Request](https://office.visualstudio.com/DefaultCollection/OC/_git/office-bohemia/pullrequest/2033141)\n     9→\n    10→## Background\n    11→\n    12→This is an augmentation on Loop's Copilot feature which has its original design detailed in [this document](./20230116-Copilot-Component.md).  Loop Copilot's initial version uses user-typed asks to create LLM prompts and display a response, with the ability for users to both refine the response with futher LLM prompts as well as make manual edits.  The goal of this feature is to heavily leverage the existing Copilot feature and ongoing efforts within it, as well as add support for:\n    13→\n    14→1. Incorporating current page content into an LLM prompt.  (Prior to this work Copilot would solely reason about user-typed asks/refiners and the latest working content.)\n    15→2. Supporting a known request type (ex. page summary) without the user having to type an ask.\n    16→\n    17→## Problem Statement\n    18→\n    19→Augment the Copilot feature in order to support the ability to add a Copilot block that automatically generates a summary of the current Loop page with a single click from the / menu on that page.\n    20→\n    21→## Design Requirements\n    22→\n    23→1. The \"Page summary\" option in the / menu is available on Loop pages for users with AI features enabled, while the Copilot block with the response is visible even for users without AI features.\n    24→2. The initial request for page summary fetches current page content and incorporates that into a summary-specific LLM prompt.\n    25→3. Like with other asks in the Copilot block, users can perform manual edits and refinement asks to a page summary, and refinements will be based on current working content.  We will not consult the page for further updates in a refinement, so this will behave like Copilot does today.\n    26→4. The user has the ability to add the Page summary Copilot block to the page multiple times.\n    27→5. The page summary should be in the same language as the page (or language determined to be primary on page if multiple), if a supported language for AI.\n    28→6. Page content used for the summary will minimally include all text (including within lists, tables, other Copilot blocks, etc.) from the main page body, as well as formatting information.\n    29→7. Page Summary should provide a reasonable failure message in error conditions. (Possible failures include failed to retrieve page content, page content empty, page content deemed harmful/offensive, page content language not yet supported for AI, etc.)\n    30→\n    31→### Post-MVP/Non-Goals/Out-of-Scope for MVP\n    32→\n    33→1. Longer term we would like to support properly utilizing page content when the user types an ask that requires page content (ex. \"Summarize this page\" among others).  In-progress work by the core Copilot crew should eventually account for this scenario.  It's possible the timeframe may be comparable to our feature or not long after, but it's being treated as a separate scope from our feature, which is focused on the ask-free page summary generation and not arbitary asks that benefit from page content awareness.\n    34→2. Longer term we would like the ability to regenerate a summary based on latest content, but due to nuances of losing any further refinements/edits and potential confusion if Copilot supports rerunning the latest LLM ask (which is different from our start-over refresh), this is out of scope for MVP.  A workaround is the user can add a second Page Summary Copilot block from scratch or manually update an existing summary to reflect the most up-to-date content.\n    35→3. Support for representing other page content not handled by MVP (ex. nested pages, table metadata, some representation of images/video, etc.).\n    36→\n    37→## Proposed Solutions (including alternative solutions considered)\n    38→\n    39→### Scenarios instead of asks\n    40→\n    41→The initial Loop Copilot request was largely based around providing a user-typed ask.  With the new pattern of generating a request without a user-typed ask, we are introducing a new Copilot request parameter/type for a \"scenario\".  A scenario is a replacement for an ask when the user intent is known, and we want to hold a higher bar of ensuring the LLM behaves appropriately.  Alongside the `initialAsk` and `refinerAsk` in `ILoopCopilotRequest`, we have `initialScenario` whose type is effectively a string enum but initially only supports \"PageSummary\".  If this is set with an unexpected value, the request immediately fails.  If the type is a known value, we choose the prompt and its args accordingly to get the best experience for that scenario, including getting and providing page content for the PageSummary scenario.  Initially, since the PageSummary scenario is just for an initial request, we will not support a `refinerScenario` and still expect user-typed asks for refinements.\n    42→\n    43→One alternative includes simply using the existing `initialAsk` and special casing some string as the page summary request.  However, this has a few issues:\n    44→\n    45→1. As Copilot expands to support non-English languages, either an always-English hard-coded string could incorrectly imply the user prefers English, or we'd have to have to deduce from many localized strings conveying a page summary request, which is not a good pattern to use especially as we grow to support more languages.\n    46→2. Until we support user-typed asks for page summary (#1 in Post-MVP above), it would be misleading if we had one specific ask string that happens to work while other similar strings do not.\n    47→3. Even after we support user-typed asks for page summary, there's always the possibility reasoning about a user-typed ask (aside from comparing for an exact value) may get misinterpreted by the LLM, so to have a higher bar for known intent when the user explicitly clicks on a \"Page summary\" button instead of submitting a typed message, it makes more sense to explicitly convey this with a new field.\n    48→\n    49→For backwards compatibility reasons, a Copilot history item that comes from a scenario will still persist a user-friendly localized string representation of the scenario to the `ask` field in the history item data.  This is used as a display string for the history item and shown at the top of the Copilot block.  Older clients may not know about scenarios and populating the ask will still allow them to render reasonably.  Newer clients can optionally render differently on history items with a persisted `scenario` field, such as potentially localizing the ask string for the current user instead of for the user who requested the summary (though we currently plan to just use the persisted ask field for MVP, in the language of the summary requester).  The persisted scenario also allows us to capture more telemetry around scenario-based flows, like when refinements were originally from a scenario vs. a user ask.\n    50→\n    51→The other use for the ask is as the `initialAsk` field in a refiner prompt.  At this time we believe we can use the same refiner prompts as existing Copilot usage, and will likewise use a string representation of any provided `initialScenario` (ex. \"Page summary\" or \"Summarize the page\") for the `initialAsk` placeholder in the refiner prompt.\n    52→\n    53→### Providing Page Content to the Prompt\n    54→\n    55→The initial design document for Copilot (linked above) references it uses a SingleItemWorkflow, but more recently it has started to transition to a [ReduceWorkflow](https://web.augloop-tools.officeppe.com/api/classes/_augloop_api_workflows.ReduceWorkflow).  The ReduceWorkflow enables getting TextTiles from the page context representing page context which we can provide in executing the loopCopilotLambda.  We will perform some basic validation on the page content (ex. emptiness) and return an error on failure, and otherwise the content is provided to the prompt.  We will use a new prompt specific to page summary that uses the page content and not an `initialAsk`.  This new prompt includes rules about how to write a summary, such as a target range for number of bullet points, etc.  Like the other prompts, there will be RAI checks on the result.\n    56→\n    57→## New Contracts/Public APIs\n    58→\n    59→This will heavily leverage existing Copilot work.  The main contract change is the new `initialScenario` optional property on `ILoopCopilotRequest`.\n    60→\n    61→## Data & Backwards Compatibility\n    62→\n    63→As discussed previously, the history item for the scenario will populate the existing `ask` field with the string \"Page summary\" even though there was no user ask, for backward compatibility purposes.  We also persist the scenario as a new optional field.  In both cases, these are fixed strings (localized for ask, an enum for scenario) and hence there are no privacy concerns.\n    64→\n    65→In addition to Copilot augmentations for page summary, our crew is helping to fund select somewhat-related other general augmentations to Copilot.  This includes persisting ML request timestamps on their history items as a new optional field, as it could be useful to know the point in time a summary was generated from the page content.  We will likely not fund displaying these timestamps as part of MVP and will wait until we have clearer UI designs, and also do not see any privacy concerns.\n    66→\n    67→In both cases, this involves the existing `CopilotHistoryItem` persisted data types, and is just adding new optional fields to it.  We would not change the persistent data model Copilot uses more than that.\n    68→\n    69→## Service / Package Dependencies & Security\n    70→\n    71→This is dependent on Loop Copilot and its use of AugLoop.  Our crew has been partnering with the Copilot crew and see ourselves as an extension of that team, now joining in some of their meetings, conversations, PRs, etc.  We do not have any other dependent partners/packages at this time.  There are no new security/authentication behaviors/concerns outside of existing Loop Copilot.\n    72→\n    73→## Accessibility\n    74→\n    75→The / menu entry point will have the same accessibility behaviors as the rest of the menu.  After invoking that control, the remaining UI behaviors come from the existing Copilot feature.  There aren't any new accessibility concerns for Page Summary on top of core Copilot.\n    76→\n    77→Any new UI our team may add to help augment core Copilot (ex. a Copy button to copy the response) will be made accessible.\n    78→\n    79→## Mobile Ship Bar\n    80→\n    81→This generally comes from core Copilot.  Whatever mobile experience is delivered for Copilot will be reflected for our augmentation of Copilot.\n    82→\n    83→## Performance\n    84→\n    85→For an existing component, the behaviors will be the same as any other Copilot block, so any page load performance is covered by metrics for Copilot itself.  The initial PR for this feature reported 1.63KB impact to loop-app and loop-page-container, with follow up changes also being small (ex. ~200 bytes for the changes to persist new history item fields).  We are not introducing any new package dependencies.\n    86→\n    87→The most interesting performance metrics for this specific augmentation is time to generate a page summary.  We are adding new fields to indicate the scenario (ex. PageSummary) when applicable to be able to filter data by scenario on Copilot's activity for the ML request and any other relevant Copilot telemetry.\n    88→\n    89→One other new-to-Copilot change is the inclusion of page content in the LLM prompt.  For this Copilot has started flighting switching to a Reduce workflow in Augloop with access to the TextTiles on the page, and we will on demand when needed compute a page content string from the text tiles as part of the Augloop request for page summary.  This is included in the LLM prompt and could have an impact on the request time, though as noted in the Copilot document it is expected that \"LLM interactions are high latency (~5s)\".\n    90→\n    91→One other nuance is that the / menu entry point immediately generates a request to the LLM, so it lowers the bar to entry for putting more load on the LLM servers, but still requires explicit user interaction for this.\n    92→\n    93→Since this is an augmentation of Copilot, we intend to leverage the goals and dashboards established by Copilot but need to support filtering by scenario in the dashboard and any relevant reports to get the relevant numbers for our specific feature.\n    94→\n    95→Performance review was held on 6/12/2023 with no new concerns.\n    96→\n    97→## Staying Aware and Notifications\n    98→\n    99→While this feature is considered part of the Staying Aware job as it helps users to more quickly consume page content, this does not merit any additional notifications.\n   100→\n   101→## Flighting\n   102→\n   103→This requires core Copilot to be enabled, which necessitates:\n   104→'copilot.enabled' - Component feature flag.\n   105→AI Enabled - for public preview there will be an additional setting required to enable AI features.\n   106→\n   107→We have recently heard of a possible setting to disable UI features with user-typed asks while keeping other \"scenario\"-based AI features like this.  In that event, we may revisit our gating to be able to light up Page Summary independently, but that is currently considered out of scope for initial rollout, which will depend on core Copilot flights.\n   108→\n   109→Additionally, this requires the flighted change to switch to the reduce workflow for Loop Copilot:\n   110→'augloop.loopCopilotReduceWorkflow'\n   111→\n   112→For our feature itself, to reduce the risk of someone finding out feature gate in code and lighting it up, we are opting to use a GUID and have generated the following GUID for this purpose:\n   113→'17A39967-0399-4499-8871-A92FCC0FB84A'\n   114→\n   115→## Feature Observability\n   116→\n   117→Loop Copilot already has telemetry events such as CopilotComponentInitialized.  We have added a new data field for the scenario on relevant Copilot and Augloop telemetry to filter these activities to our specific scenario in order to measure usage and failures for page summary, including creating Copilot blocks with an initial scenario, the initial scenario-based request itself, and refinement requests when the initial request used a scenarios.\n   118→\n   119→## Privacy\n   120→\n   121→We do not see any new privacy concerns with our augmentation of Copilot and the previous privacy review of Copilot was deemed sufficient.\n   122→\n   123→## Globalization\n   124→\n   125→This feature will for the most part use the same localization plan as Copilot, supporting tier 1 languages to start, when Copilot is ready for this.  Our strings will be localized in the UI.  At this time we are generating the summary in the primary language of the page content, with planned future ability for Copilot to translate to another language with a refinement.\n   126→\n   127→## Responsible AI\n   128→\n   129→We had our RAI review on 5/31/2023 in which it was suggested that the summary scenario does not require input validation of the page content since it is user content, and validation of the output (as already exists for Loop Copilot) suffices.  Furthermore, it was suggested that for the summary scenario specifically (unlike other Loop Copilot scenarios) we could optionally return a response with detected \"harmful language\" if we also confirm it is found in the page content, to reduce the number of failed responses.  This is only considered viable for a summary because its source was the page rather than being created by the AI.  We do not intend to invest in that potential improvement in the initial release but could consider it in the future.\n   130→\n   131→## Next Steps\n   132→\n   133→(This section should be filled in as the design review progresses. It should include specific next steps, ADO items and timelines for after the design docs has been finalized.)\n   134→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUCvAHSXRtjX93sY9sKE3i","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"1bda17e8-c9ed-4125-8187-0c2d12704c6f"}
