{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MikdYHUoaScAcnbwfBPLBW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * @officeagent/message-protocol/types\n     3→ *\n     4→ * WebSocket message protocol contract\n     5→ */\n     6→\n     7→import { MessageType } from './message-type';\n     8→import type { Message as SydneyMessage } from '@augloop-types/sydney';\n     9→\n    10→// Re-export MessageType for convenience\n    11→export { MessageType };\n    12→export { Message as SydneyMessage } from '@augloop-types/sydney';\n    13→\n    14→/**\n    15→ * Base schema interface for all messages\n    16→ */\n    17→export interface Schema {\n    18→    /** What this message is */\n    19→    type: MessageType;\n    20→    /** Message ID */\n    21→    id: string;\n    22→}\n    23→\n    24→/**\n    25→ * Base message interface for all WebSocket messages\n    26→ * @template T - The type of the payload\n    27→ */\n    28→export interface Message<T = unknown> extends Schema {\n    29→    /** Session which message is for */\n    30→    sessionId: string;\n    31→    /** Message payload - can be any object */\n    32→    payload: T;\n    33→}\n    34→\n    35→/**\n    36→ * Response message interface that extends base Message\n    37→ * Used for messages that are responses to previous requests\n    38→ */\n    39→export interface ResponseMessage<T = unknown> extends Message<T> {\n    40→    /** ID of the request this is responding to */\n    41→    requestId: string;\n    42→}\n    43→\n    44→/**\n    45→ * OfficePy Settings\n    46→ * Contains configuration settings to be passed to the OfficePy container\n    47→ * Each setting is a key-value pair where the value can be boolean, string, or number\n    48→ */\n    49→export interface OfficePySettings {\n    50→    /** Settings as key-value pairs */\n    51→    [key: string]: boolean | string | number | object;\n    52→}\n    53→\n    54→/**\n    55→ * Scenario type enum for differentiating between enterprise and consumer contexts\n    56→ * Used to filter themes, layouts, and other scenario-specific features\n    57→ */\n    58→export enum ScenarioType {\n    59→    /** Consumer/personal use scenarios */\n    60→    Consumer = 'consumer',\n    61→    /** Enterprise/business use scenarios */\n    62→    Enterprise = 'enterprise'\n    63→}\n    64→\n    65→/**\n    66→ * Grounding Source flags to enable or disable specific grounding sources\n    67→ * Contains OCPS (Office Copilot Service) policy settings and user sources preferences that control feature availability\n    68→ */\n    69→export interface IGroundingSourceToggles {\n    70→    /** Flag to enable/disable web search functionality */\n    71→    webSearch: boolean;\n    72→\n    73→    /** Flag to enable/disable enterprise search */\n    74→    enterpriseSearch: boolean;\n    75→}\n    76→\n    77→/**\n    78→ * Client metadata containing details about the client calling Agents\n    79→ */\n    80→export interface ClientMetadata {"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUCvAHSXRtjX93sY9sKE3i","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"99702954-7d51-4276-81a9-0429bfd86441"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RDXRZd2D26vVqMEKwHef5X","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Package Integration\n     2→\n     3→This document shares information about the release of Loop's NPM packages and CDN-delivered assets. It contains details about what is released, the schedule and expectations around hosts picking up new versions. It is meant to serve as a guide for hosts to effectively integrate and update Loop experiences.\n     4→\n     5→## What is released?\n     6→\n     7→![Screenshot of a Loop Component loaded in a Teams message. Blue highlight shows 'outside' and red highlight shows 'inside'](.images/screenshot-teams-message-highlight-npm-vs-cdn.png)\n     8→*The outside (host ux/owh loading/injected dependencies) is always NPM delivered. The inside (loop component experience) may be CDN or NPM delivered (in 1js/npm hosts)*\n     9→\n    10→1. NPM packages for things that are integrated directly by hosts: bootstrapping/wrapper-ux logic, etc. ([host-ux](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_artifacts/feed/Office/Npm/@fluidx%2Fhost-ux/overview/41.53.3), [office-web-host](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_artifacts/feed/Office/Npm/@ms%2Foffice-web-host/), [injected-dependencies](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_artifacts/feed/Office/Npm/@fluidx%2Finjected-dependencies), etc.)\n    11→2. CDN-delivered assets for the loop-page-container and office-fluid-container (i.e., which bring the scriptor, tablero, and other core experiences), as well as the service-delivered drivers.\n    12→   - [Sample dogfood manifest (on CDN) which points to other CDN assets to load](https://cdn.fluidpreview.office.net/fluid/df/container/versionless/officeContainerCodeLoadDetails.json)\n    13→   - ***Note***: Hosts don't need to worry about deployment, rollback, or hotfix of these assets. That's handled by Loop OCEs. Hosts can, however, ask to be part of the validation process (Teams does).\n    14→\n    15→> [!NOTE]\n    16→> Loop App does use NPM for some traditionally CDN-delivered assets (loop-page-container), and we're working (with OWA, for now) on enabling hosts to integrate loop component experiences via NPM. For now, majority of hosts get loop component experiences from CDN and bootstrapping/wrapper-ux logic from NPM.\n    17→\n    18→## When are they released?\n    19→\n    20→- For NPM, packages are built and published **twice a day** by our pipelines.\n    21→  - Publish pipeline for LoopSDK: [Pipelines - Runs for LoopSDK - NPM Publish (visualstudio.com)](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_build?definitionId=20202)\n    22→  - Publish pipeline for everything else: [Pipelines - Runs for office-bohemia npm publish (visualstudio.com)](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_build?definitionId=9884)\n    23→  - If needed, we have the option to create hotfix NPM packages. We try to use this option sparingly; but if a host cannot quickly bump to new versions, and if there is a bug fix that's needed ASAP for NPM-delivered code, we can make a hotfix branch. That way, the host can be sure that no other changes (and possible regressions, and/or nested-dependency issues) come from the alternative of just jumping to the latest of everything. See the [\"Consuming NPM Hotfix packages\"](#consuming-npm-hotfix-packages) section below for more information\n    24→- For CDN, assets (for Fluid-based Loop Components from [the office-bohemia repo](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_git/office-bohemia)) are released roughly **twice a week** unless there are blockers like build issues or regressions. For those, we occasionally deploy hotfixes directly to dogfood/prod, and you'll be notified on [the Components Teams channel](https://teams.microsoft.com/l/channel/19%3a35fe577568f243b3904d5cab2c79d374%40thread.skype/Components%2520%25F0%259F%2593%25A6?groupId=422665a0-7ad3-4d0d-9171-e8881d0397d9&tenantId=72f988bf-86f1-41af-91ab-2d7cd011db47) when we do.\n    25→\n    26→> [!NOTE]\n    27→> Other 2P components (components outside office-bohemia) might have their own service cadence if delivered by CDN.\n    28→\n    29→## How often to pick up newly released minor/patch versions?\n    30→\n    31→- There is no hard requirement for when to pick them up. However, we've found that a cadence of **once a month is good to shoot for**, especially during active feature development. We strongly recommend doing so as soon as feasible to avoid complications when you suddenly need to pick up a new version of a package (e.g., host-ux) for a new feature or bug fix. In those moments, complications like dependency issues will only get in your way.\n    32→- ***Info***: Old versions will continue to work for a long time. Some deployed apps such as in Teams/Outlook Win32 sometimes use OWH versions from a year ago.\n    33→- ***Info***: For very small changes, some (e.g. Teams) have had success with using patch-package to inject small changes without picking up new versions.\n    34→\n    35→## On upgrading to newly-released NPM packages\n    36→\n    37→Since the logistics of CDN-delivered assets is handled by us, you'll mostly be dealing with integrating NPM packages. Here's some more info on handling them:\n    38→\n    39→> [!IMPORTANT]\n    40→> When upgrading, you'll have the best experience picking up all packages in unison (i.e., pick up a given day's latest OWH, host-ux, etc. together). This will avoid weird types/sub-dependencies issues since we use a mono-repo. See more in the [\"Given a particular package version, how to find matching NPM versions of other packages\"](#given-a-particular-package-version-how-to-find-matching-npm-versions-of-other-packages) section below.\n    41→\n    42→- NPM packages follow [semver](https://semver.org/). Unless there's a major bump, minors/patches should be perfectly compatible as is\n    43→- If you'd like to know more about the changes in each package, you can [view their changelogs](https://office.visualstudio.com/OC/_search?action=contents&text=file%3A%20CHANGELOG.md&type=code&lp=code-Project&filters=ProjectFilters%7BOC%7DRepositoryFilters%7BLoopSDK*office-bohemia%7D&pageSize=25&result=DefaultCollection/OC/LoopSDK/GBmain//packages/loop-sdk/CHANGELOG.md), for example, [CHANGELOG for @ms/office-web-host](https://office.visualstudio.com/oc/_git/office-bohemia?path=/packages/office-web-host/CHANGELOG.md&_a=preview)\n    44→- You can still use deprecated APIs, but your linter might complain. To get around that, you might have to suppress the warning (e.g. in ESLint), or follow the deprecation instructions\n    45→- If you identify an issue with an old version, we recommend picking up the latest OWH/host-ux/whichever package has the issue. We could patch the individual package, but since we release new versions up to twice a day, it is impractical to do so.\n    46→- OWH, as well as many other packages, depends on fluid-framework (FF), which has its own cadence. In general, FF changes should be transparent to consumers of OWH. **When bumping OWH and others, you'll need to also bump FF dependencies to corresponding versions** (e.g., referring to the `package.json` of the received OWH version).\n    47→  - ***Note***: FF release frequency is different and faster than OWH's. A given \"minor\" of OWH might also bring in a major of FF. This can cause problems with duplicate major versions being pulled in if two different packages are requesting two different non-resolvable things. See this thread for more info: [Michael Zlatkovsky: Unblocking Teams to pick up new version of Loop packages](https://teams.microsoft.com/l/message/19:24e2f83fd3be4313b63b221b6d634e98@thread.skype/1695157139130?tenantId=72f988bf-86f1-41af-91ab-2d7cd011db47&groupId=422665a0-7ad3-4d0d-9171-e8881d0397d9&parentMessageId=1695157139130&teamName=Loop&channelName=Teams%20Ch1&createdTime=1695157139130)\n    48→\n    49→## What about major bumps?\n    50→\n    51→**We plan to do them 2 to 4 times per year**, mainly to remove any deprecated APIs. Once we are a few weeks away from a major bump, we'll give you a heads-up via the Fluid Framework Experiences Partners distribution list (<ffxpartners@microsoft.com>) and Teams channel notification. This will allow you to schedule time to integrate the update. We will also notify you once the bump is complete.\n    52→\n    53→- **How soon should we do a major upgrade?** As soon as feasible after it is released. While there's no strict requirement, you won't be able to pick up new features or bug fixes to NPM-delivered code until you do so.\n    54→  - **How long would you continue to support an older major version?** Our support for older major versions spans up to six months, during which we'll support the current major version and the one before it. For example, if the current version is 15, you'll have support if you're on 14 or 15. Once 16 is released, you'll have six months to upgrade.\n    55→- **How painful is it?** API removals will require some re-working of code. Ideally, if you follow the `@deprecated` notices during earlier minor bumps, you will have moved off of any to-be-removed APIs already, and it will be fairly smooth sailing.\n    56→- **When do you remove deprecated APIs?** Typically, we remove deprecated artifacts after a single major bump cycle. For example, if something has been deprecated in OWH 14 for over three months (one quarterly cycle), we expect to remove it in version 15. However, exceptions may be made under special circumstances, in which case you will be notified via Teams.\n    57→\n    58→## Given a particular package version, how to find matching NPM versions of other packages?\n    59→\n    60→If you've been told to use a particular version number of a particular package, how can you figure out what other package versions to pick up, especially if you aren't using the very very latest of everything? The process is actually pretty easy."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUCvAHSXRtjX93sY9sKE3i","session_id":"d982c5f4-98da-4461-b748-c7175dcade88","uuid":"da56b404-37a0-456c-a653-553baf8f5179"}
